title: HCMINdepthMore
tags: 
speaker: Evyln
colorID: 8
position: -373,-1490
---
Of course, $userFirstName! 

In HCM, the muscle wall of the heart is thickened.
This thickening is usually mainly in the muscle

wall between the right ventricle and the left ventricle, also referred to as the septum.
If the muscle

wall is slightly thickened, the contraction is usually still good and the heart pumps out the blood

properly.
With a severely thickened heart muscle, the heart muscle becomes stiffer and the heart

muscle is less able to relax, causing the left ventricle to fill less well with blood.
The amount of blood

that the left ventricle can pump out is therefore reduced, causing less oxygen-rich blood to enter

the body.

Sometimes the septum becomes so thickened that it gets in the way of the blood that needs to be

pumped out of the heart.
This is then referred to as 'Hypertrophic Obstructive Cardiomyopathy'

(HOCM).
People with HOCM often have difficulty with exertion, may feel unwell with even minor

exertion and sometimes faint during exertion.

The disease can also cause damage to the heart muscle.
Cardiac muscle cells can die and are then

replaced by connective tissue.
The heart can then contract less well and pump blood.
This can also

disrupt electrical activity in the heart.
This can cause cardiac arrhythmias that can cause someone

to faint.
Sometimes this can also cause someone to die suddenly.

With an ECG at rest or during exercise, the heart rhythm can be examined and indications of HCM

can be seen.
Sometimes a 24-hour heart film is necessary to detect cardiac arrhythmias.

The mobility and pumping function of the heart can usually be clearly examined with an ultrasound.

Sometimes an MRI scan is necessary to get a better look at the heart. Damage to the heart can be

visualized with an MRI scan of the heart with contrast fluid.

