Our body is made up of billions of cells, each doing specific jobs (like heart cells or nerve cells). Inside these cells are chromosomes, which are tightly packed strands of DNA. DNA holds all the genetic information, and this information is stored in genes, which are sections of DNA.
Genes act as instructions for how your body works—everything from your hair color to how your organs function. You inherit one version of each gene from your biological parents. A problem in a gene (called a mutation or variant) can disrupt its function, potentially leading to health issues.


