Adult children
If the DNA test shows that you have the hereditary predisposition, you would do well to tell any adult children about it. The advice is not to wait; there may be a risk to their health. Tensions may also arise between you and your children.

If it turns out that you have the hereditary predisposition, your adult children are eligible for a check-up with a heart specialist. Even if you decide not to test, any children you may have are eligible for this. If your DNA test shows that you have no hereditary predisposition, then checking your children is not necessary.

Minor children
When, what and how you tell your minor children about the hereditary disease obviously depends on the age and development of your child(ren). It can be difficult for young children to understand what it is about and what the consequences may be. It is often good to tell children step by step.

If it turns out that you have the hereditary predisposition, minor children are eligible for a check-up with a pediatric cardiologist, from the age of 10 to 12 years. Even if you decide not to test, any children you may have are eligible for this. If your DNA test shows that you have no hereditary predisposition, then checking your children is not necessary.

